Ca2+-saturated CaM binds to peptides by “grasping” target sequences, 
in helical conformation, between N- and C-terminal domains.  In many
cases, this activates an enzyme by sequestering an inhibitory domain
(e.g. M13 from MLCK).  Interactions between CaM and targets involve
hydrophobic contact area and charge-charge interactions.

